  <p>On June 29, 2026, the 2026 World Cup's Round of 32 delivered exactly the sort of fixtures that make a betting board glow: Brazil against Japan, Germany against Paraguay, Netherlands against Morocco — storied names beside teams that many casual bettors would struggle to place on a map. For anyone scrolling the app, the eye goes straight to the badge it knows. Brazil. Germany. France a day later against Sweden. These are not just teams; they are memories, anthems, players you grew up watching lift trophies. Backing them feels less like a gamble and more like siding with the obvious.</p>

  <p>That feeling is the subject of this piece. We do not publish tips or picks, and this is not one. But the comfort of the famous name is one of the most reliable ways a bettor overpays, because it runs on a well-documented mental shortcut — familiarity bias, the brain's habit of trusting what it recognises — and that shortcut, harmless in daily life, quietly moves the odds against you on a betting board built to reward exactly this instinct.</p>

