  <h2>Why the brain treats a famous name as a safe one</h2>

  <p>Familiarity bias is one of the most studied shortcuts in decision-making. Faced with a quick judgment and incomplete information, the mind reaches for what it recognises and tags it as safer, better, more trustworthy — because in ordinary life, the familiar usually is. We choose the brand we know, the route we have driven, the restaurant we have eaten at. The shortcut saves effort and is mostly harmless. On a betting board it misfires, because what the shortcut is actually measuring — how well you know a team — has almost nothing to do with what the bet requires you to predict: whether that team will win this particular match, at this price.</p>

  <p>The two things feel like one. "I know Brazil are good" slides effortlessly into "Brazil are a good bet", and the slide happens beneath conscious thought. You are not weighing Brazil's form against Japan's organisation and the price on offer; you are recognising a badge and feeling reassured. The recognition does the work that analysis should, and it does it with a confidence the analysis would not always support. The unfamiliar opponent, meanwhile, gets no such glow — you know little about Japan or Paraguay or Morocco, so they feel riskier, vaguer, easier to bet against, regardless of what the actual matchup says.</p>

  <div class="pull-quote">
    <p>Knowing a team is not the same as knowing the bet. The badge you recognise is measuring your memory, not the match.</p>
